ASSIGNMENT OVERVIEW¶

This assignment requires you to implement and compare two CNN approaches for image classification:

  1. Custom CNN architecture using Keras/PyTorch
  2. Transfer Learning using pre-trained models (ResNet/VGG)

Learning Objectives:

  • Design CNN architectures with Global Average Pooling
  • Apply transfer learning with pre-trained models
  • Compare custom vs pre-trained model performance
  • Use industry-standard deep learning frameworks

IMPORTANT: Global Average Pooling (GAP) is MANDATORY for both models. DO NOT use Flatten + Dense layers in the final architecture.

import tensorflow_datasets as tfds
import tensorflow as tf

# REQUIRED metadata fields (template variables)

problem_type = "classification"

# Image config (good for transfer learning)
IMG_SIZE = (224, 224)
BATCH_SIZE = 32

# Load full dataset (TFDS malaria is stored under split 'train')
ds_all, ds_info = tfds.load(
    "malaria",
    split="train",
    as_supervised=True,
    with_info=True
)

# Class info from TFDS
class_names = ds_info.features["label"].names  # typically: ['parasitized', 'uninfected']
n_classes = ds_info.features["label"].num_classes

# Total samples
n_samples = ds_info.splits["train"].num_examples

# Assignment required train/test split: 85/15
train_test_ratio = "85/15"
train_size = int(0.85 * n_samples)
test_size = n_samples - train_size

# Deterministic shuffle then split
ds_all = ds_all.shuffle(10000, seed=SEED, reshuffle_each_iteration=False)
train_raw_full = ds_all.take(train_size)
test_raw = ds_all.skip(train_size)

train_samples = train_size
test_samples = test_size

# Recommended: create a validation split from training set (10% of train)
val_size = int(0.10 * train_samples)
val_raw = train_raw_full.take(val_size)
train_raw = train_raw_full.skip(val_size)

# Preprocess: resize + normalize
def preprocess(image, label):
    image = tf.image.resize(image, IMG_SIZE)
    image = tf.cast(image, tf.float32) / 255.0
    label = tf.cast(label, tf.int32)
    return image, label

train_ds = train_raw.map(preprocess).batch(BATCH_SIZE).prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)
val_ds   = val_raw.map(preprocess).batch(BATCH_SIZE).prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)
test_ds  = test_raw.map(preprocess).batch(BATCH_SIZE).prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)

# Count per-class samples (for requirement visibility)
def count_classes(ds_unbatched, n_classes):
    counts = [0] * n_classes
    for _, y in ds_unbatched:
        counts[int(y.numpy())] += 1
    return counts

train_counts = count_classes(train_raw, n_classes)
val_counts   = count_classes(val_raw, n_classes)
test_counts  = count_classes(test_raw, n_classes)

)

IMG_SIZE = (224, 224)

custom_cnn = build_custom_cnn((IMG_SIZE[0], IMG_SIZE[1], 3), n_classes)


def build_custom_cnn(input_shape, n_classes):
    """
    Custom CNN with Global Average Pooling (MANDATORY).
    NO Flatten layers used.
    """
    inputs = keras.Input(shape=input_shape)

    x = layers.Conv2D(32, 3, padding="same")(inputs)
    x = layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
    x = layers.ReLU()(x)
    x = layers.MaxPooling2D()(x)

    x = layers.Conv2D(64, 3, padding="same")(x)
    x = layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
    x = layers.ReLU()(x)
    x = layers.MaxPooling2D()(x)

    x = layers.Conv2D(128, 3, padding="same")(x)
    x = layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
    x = layers.ReLU()(x)

    # MANDATORY: Global Average Pooling
    x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)

    x = layers.Dropout(0.3)(x)
    outputs = layers.Dense(n_classes, activation="softmax")(x)

    model = keras.Model(inputs, outputs, name="custom_cnn_gap")
    model.compile(
        optimizer=keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=1e-3),
        loss="sparse_categorical_crossentropy",
        metrics=["accuracy"]
    )
    return model

custom_cnn = build_custom_cnn((IMG_SIZE[0], IMG_SIZE[1], 3), n_classes)
custom_cnn.summary()

PART 3: TRANSFER LEARNING IMPLEMENTATION (5 MARKS)¶

REQUIREMENTS:

  • Use pre-trained model: ResNet18/ResNet50 OR VGG16/VGG19
  • Freeze base layers (feature extractor)
  • Replace final layers with:
    • Global Average Pooling (GAP) - MANDATORY
    • Custom classification head
  • Fine-tune on your dataset
  • Track initial_loss and final_loss

GRADING:

  • Valid base model with frozen layers: 2 marks
  • GAP + custom head properly implemented: 1 mark
  • Training completed with loss tracking: 1 mark
  • All metrics calculated correctly: 1 mark

pretrained_model_name = "ResNet50"

def build_transfer_learning_model(base_model_name, input_shape, n_classes):
    """
    Builds a transfer learning model with:
    - Pretrained backbone (ImageNet)
    - Frozen base layers (MANDATORY)
    - Global Average Pooling (MANDATORY)
    - NO Flatten used
    """
    if base_model_name == "ResNet50":
        base_model = keras.applications.ResNet50(
            weights="imagenet",
            include_top=False,
            input_shape=input_shape
        )
        preprocess_fn = keras.applications.resnet.preprocess_input

    elif base_model_name == "VGG16":
        base_model = keras.applications.VGG16(
            weights="imagenet",
            include_top=False,
            input_shape=input_shape
        )
        preprocess_fn = keras.applications.vgg16.preprocess_input

    elif base_model_name == "VGG19":
        base_model = keras.applications.VGG19(
            weights="imagenet",
            include_top=False,
            input_shape=input_shape
        )
        preprocess_fn = keras.applications.vgg19.preprocess_input

    else:
        raise ValueError("Supported base_model_name: ResNet50, VGG16, VGG19")

    # MANDATORY: Freeze base model
    base_model.trainable = False

    inputs = keras.Input(shape=input_shape)

    # Preprocess input according to the chosen model
    x = layers.Lambda(preprocess_fn, name="preprocess")(inputs)

    x = base_model(x, training=False)

    # MANDATORY: Global Average Pooling
    x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D(name="gap")(x)

    x = layers.Dropout(0.3)(x)
    outputs = layers.Dense(n_classes, activation="softmax")(x)

    model = keras.Model(inputs, outputs, name=f"{base_model_name}_transfer_gap")

    model.compile(
        optimizer=keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=1e-3),
        loss="sparse_categorical_crossentropy",
        metrics=["accuracy"]
    )
    return model, base_model

analysis_text = """
The custom CNN clearly outperformed the transfer learning model across all evaluation metrics.
The custom CNN achieved an accuracy of 93.93% with macro-averaged precision, recall, and F1-score
close to 0.94, whereas the ResNet50-based transfer learning model achieved an accuracy of
approximately 63% with an F1-score around 0.63. This represents an absolute improvement of
about 31% in accuracy in favor of the custom CNN.

Training from scratch proved more effective in this case because the custom CNN learned
features directly from domain-specific malaria cell images. In contrast, the pretrained
ResNet50 model relied on ImageNet features, which are better suited to natural images and
did not transfer effectively to microscopic medical imagery, leading to slower convergence
and underfitting.

Global Average Pooling (GAP) played an important role in both models by significantly reducing
the number of trainable parameters and helping to prevent overfitting while preserving
important spatial information.

From a computational perspective, the custom CNN was more efficient, using approximately
94 thousand parameters compared to about 2.36 crore parameters in the transfer learning
model, although it required slightly more training time.

Overall, these results suggest that transfer learning is most effective when pretrained
features closely match the target domain, whereas custom CNNs can outperform frozen
pretrained models on specialized medical imaging tasks.
"""

# Print analysis with word count
print("\n" + "="*70)
print("ANALYSIS")
print("="*70)
print(analysis_text)
print("="*70)
print(f"Analysis word count: {len(analysis_text.split())} words")
if len(analysis_text.split()) > 200:
    print("  Warning: Analysis exceeds 200 words (guideline)")
else:
    print(" Analysis within word count guideline")
